Legal_Issue: Can an interlocutory injunction be dissolved due to delay or change of circumstances in a trademark dispute?
Procedural_Stage: Interlocutory stage, motion to dissolve injunction
Evidence_Assessment: Evidence of confusion between trademarks was presented; Office Depot failed to prove substantial changes in circumstances
Decision_Outcome: Application to dissolve the interlocutory injunction is denied
Burden_of_Proof: On Office Depot to demonstrate significant delay or changed circumstances
Legal_Rule: An interlocutory injunction can be dissolved if there is significant delay or if circumstances have changed so drastically that the original order's basis is no longer valid
Procedural_Issue: Delay in proceedings and request to dissolve injunction
Outcome_on_Merits: No dissolution of injunction; parties must proceed diligently to trial
Key_Evidence_Considered: Evidence of ongoing confusion between the trademarks
Applicant_Challenge: Office Depot challenged the continuation of the injunction
Defendant_Response: Office Depot claimed no confusion exists and sought dissolution based on delay and changed circumstances
Evidence_Type: Testimonial and documentary evidence on trademark usage and public confusion
Decision_Authority: Trial court with jurisdiction over Ontario trademark matters
Claimant_Status: Business Depot as plaintiff obtaining injunction
Grounds_for_Inadmissibility_or_Allegatio: Allegation of trademark infringement and likelihood of confusion
Outcome_of_Review: No change to injunction; case proceeds to trial
Governing_Rule: Common law principles on interlocutory injunctions and trademark protection
